<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is found in the epipelagic (0-200 m depth) and mesopelagic zones (200-500 m depth) of the Pacific, Indian and Atlantic Oceans (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
), the Indian water (
<bibRefCitation author="George, PC" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="657 - 689" refId="B28" refString="George, PC, 1952. A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast. Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India 18 (6): 657 - 689" title="A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast." volume="18" year="1952">George 1952</bibRefCitation>
) and the Tosa Bay in Japan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), while in this study, it was found in the epipelagic zone (0-110 m depth) of the Korea Strait and northern East China Sea (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
: stations KS05 and nECS04).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This cosmopolitan species can be found in tropical to temperate waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
). The temperature ranged between 16.40 and 16.41 °C and salinity was 34.58 psu at the sampling stations of this study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName family="Pterosagittidae" genus="K." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="K. pacifica" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">K. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a rayless zone in the lateral fin. Furthermore, the presence of a pair of lateral fins with a wide rayless zone and a fan-shaped dentition in 
<taxonomicName family="Pterosagittidae" genus="K." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="K. subtilis" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">K. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from Korean waters are consistent with the records of 
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
(1967)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bieri, R" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="122 - 136" refId="B8" refString="Bieri, R, 1991. Systematics of the Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 122 - 136" title="Systematics of the Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Bieri (1991)</bibRefCitation>
. However, the location of the corona ciliata (in front of the eyes, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. A Krohnitta subtilis (dorsal view) B head C tail D lateral fin. Abbreviations: CC = corona ciliata; CF = caudal fin; COL = collarette; E = eye; GS = grasping spine; IN = intestine; LF = lateral fin; RLZ = Ray less zone; SV = seminal vesicle." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704195" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">11C</figureCitation>
) of the species found in Korean waters was different from that of the previous records (located behind the eye). No specific pattern was observed through CBE staining on the body surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
